ted to Jove...: Reflections on the Poet Bertolt Brecht and His Relation to Politics -- t29. Randall Jarrell, 1914–1965 -- t30. Isak Dinesen, 1885–1962 -- t31. Notes on Dostoevsky’s Possessed -- t32. Emerson Address -- t33. Afterword to Robert Gilbert, No Donkey Has Lost Me While Galloping -- t34. Remembering Wystan H. Auden, Who Died in the Night of the Twenty-eighth of September, 1973 -- tEditorial Note: Texts in German and English -- tNotes -- tIndex -- tCrossing Aesthetics0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs one of the foremost public intellectuals of the twentieth century, Hannah Arendt is well known for her writings on political philosophy. Less familiar are her significant contributions to cultural and literary criticism. This edition brings together for the first time Arendt’s reflections on literature and culture. The essays include previously unpublished and untranslated material drawn from half a century of engagement with the works of European and American authors, poets, journalists, and literary critics, including such diverse figures as Proust, Melville, Auden, and Brecht. Intended for a wide readership, this volume has the potential to change our view of Arendt by introducing her not only as one of the leading political theorists of her generation, but also as a serious, committed, and highly original literary and cultural critic. Gottlieb’s introduction ties the work together, showing how Arendt developed a form of literary and cultural analysis that is entirely her own.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Criticism.2bisacsh1 aGottlieb, Susannah Young-ah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Backlist eBook-Package 